{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523094"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13874"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13874"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.58,0.08,0.22,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6491"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98177"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"94"},{"type":"tags","id":"2198"},{"type":"tags","id":"3012"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"6549"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man is currently admitted under the Vascular unit for intravenous antibiotic treatment of a diabetic foot ulcer. His past medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, peripheral vascular disease, coronary artery disease, obesity, and end stage kidney disease, for which he has haemodialysis three times weekly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes mellitus 15 years ago. He was initially commenced on metformin immediate-release, although was unable to tolerate this due to gastrointestinal side effects. He was then started on linagliptin and has been on this single oral agent for approximately 15 years. Since being in hospital, he was started on a basal-bolus insulin regimen due to persistently raised blood glucose levels between 15-19 mmol/L. On discharge, the patient adamantly declines insulin but is open to considering oral alternatives.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option to optimise this patients glycaemic control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence metformin extended-release","Commence empagliflozin","Change linagliptin to sitagliptin","Commence gliclazide","Commence rosiglitazone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlongside continuing linagliptin, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommencing gliclazide\u003C/strong\u003E (sulphonylurea) is appropriate in this patient with end stage kidney disease and suboptimally controlled sugars. This medication can be used in patients with end stage kidney disease on dialysis, with close monitoring of hypoglycaemia advisable. Gliclazide is considered to pose less of a hypoglycaemic risk compared to other sulphonylureas in renal impairment, due to its predominant hepatic metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E (SGLT2 inhibitor) can be commenced in patients with even late-stage chronic kidney disease so long as a eGFR \u226520ml/min per 1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. However, the effect on glycaemic control attenuates with reducing eGFR due to reduced potential for glycosuria. A recent study stated that the anticipated HbA1c drop with addition of SGLT2i for patients with eGFR:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003E60 ml/min per 1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E: 0.6-0.9%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E45-49 ml/min per 1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E: 0.3-0.5%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C45 ml/min per 1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E: minimal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENotably, SGLT2i therapy has established benefits for those with heart failure and renal disease, even in the absence of concurrent diabetes mellitus and may be of benefit to this patient for other reasons, but is not the best option for improving his glycaemic control. Furthermore, SGLT2 inhibitors are not recommended for patients on dialysis as they require some residual kidney function to exert their glycosuric effect, and there is limited safety and efficacy data for their use in this population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eextended-release metformin\u003C/strong\u003E may be less likely to cause gastrointestinal side-effects, both the immediate-release and extended-release formulation are contraindicated in patients with end stage kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELinagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esitagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E are both dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP4) inhibitors. Changing medications within the same class will not improve glycaemic control. Also note sitagliptin requires dose reduction in patients with end stage kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERosiglitazone\u003C/strong\u003E is a thiazolidinedione and is associated with adverse cardiovascular outcomes in patients with pre-existing heart disease. It is not commonly used in practice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["DPP4 inhibitors, sulphonylureas and insulin can be used for the management of type 2 diabetes mellitus in patients with end stage kidney disease on dialysis. Close monitoring for adverse effects, especially hypoglycaemia, is advised."],"references":["Caramori ML, Rossing P. Diabetic Kidney Disease [Internet]. Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, Boyce A, Chrousos G, Corpas E, et al., editors. PubMed. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000 [cited 2024 Jul 2]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279103/#:~:text=Diabetic%20nephropathy%20is%20a%20chronic,which%20can%20progress%20to%20ESKD.","Rossing P, Caramori ML, Chan JCN, Heerspink HJL, Hurst C, Khunti K, et al. Executive summary of the KDIGO 2022 Clinical Practice Guideline for Diabetes Management in Chronic Kidney Disease: an update based on rapidly emerging new evidence. Kidney International [Internet]. 2022 Nov;102(5):990\u20139. Available from: https://www.kidney-international.org/action/showPdf?pii=S0085-2538%2822%2900518-X","National Diabetes Service Scheme. Australian Type 2 Diabetes glycaemic Management Algorithm. 2024 [cited 2024 Apr 10]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/management-of-type-2-diabetes/medical-management-of-glycaemia","Yau K, Dharia A, Alrowiyti I, Cherney DZI. Prescribing sglt2 inhibitors in patients with ckd: Expanding indications and practical considerations. Kidney Int Rep. 2022;7:1463-76. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9263228/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98177"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13874"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98177"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T19:35:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T19:37:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6491"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"i